                        ܡܫܡܫܢܝܬܐ
                </span></span></h1></div><div xmlns:x="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:local="http://syriaca.org/ns"><div class="tei-note"><span xml:lang="en" lang="en" dir="ltr">Deaconess and recipient of a letter from Severus of Antioch</span><span class="tei-footnote-refs" dir="ltr" lang="en" xml:lang="en"><span class="tei-footnote-ref"><a href="#bib2597-3">3</a></span> </span></div><div style="margin:0 1em 1em; color: #999999;"><small><p><span class="srp-label"><strong>Syriaca.org URI</strong></span>: <span id="syriaca-id"><a href="http://syriaca.org/person/2597">http://syriaca.org/person/2597</a></span></p></small></div></div><div xmlns:x="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:local="http://syriaca.org/ns" class="row"><div class="col-md-8"><div class="sources"><h3>Personal Information</h3><h4>Sex: </h4><p class="indent">
                                <span class="tei-persName">Anastasia</span> 
                                was female.
                             <a href="/3125-8" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Occupation(s): </h4><p class="indent">
                                <span class="tei-persName">Anastasia</span> 
                                was a deaconess.
                             <a href="/3125-2" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent">
                                <span class="tei-persName">Anastasia the deaconess</span> 
                                was a monastic.
                             <a href="/3125-3" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p></div><div class="sources"><h3>Relationships</h3><p class="indent">
                            Anastasia and Innocent 
                            were siblings.
                         <a href="/3125-7" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent">
                            Severus and Anastasia 
                            expressed deep affection for one another in their letters.
                         <a href="/3125-9" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p></div><div class="sources"><h3>Events</h3><p class="indent">
                            Severus responded to a letter of
                            Anastasia the deaconess
                            answering her questions about 
                            Matthew 24.20 and other passages of the bible that address 
                            the end of the world.
                            
                                
                            
                         <a href="/3100-1" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">
                            Severus wrote a letter to
                            Anastasia the deaconess
                            arguing that Revelation 20.6 does not indicate
                            that there will be more than one resurrection.
                            
                                
                            
                         <a href="/3213-1" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">
                            Severus responded to a letter of
                            Anastasia the deaconess,
                            answering her questions about difficult passages in the Bible. He used allegory to explain some passages.
                            
                                
                            
                         <a href="/3125-1" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">
                            Severus wrote a letter to
                            Anastasia the deaconess
                            offering an allegorical interpretation of Psalm 127:4.
                            
                                
                            
                         <a href="/3212-1" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">
                            Anastasia the deaconess wrote a letter to
                            Severus
                            asking questions about 
                            Matthew 24.20 and other passages of the bible that address 
                            the end of the world.
                            
                                
                            
                         <a href="/3100-2" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">
                            Anastasia the deaconess wrote a letter to
                            Severus
                            asking him to clarify various difficult passages in the Bible.
                            
                                
                            
                         <a href="/3125-4" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/></div><div class="citation"><h3>How to cite:</h3><span class="element">
